\begin{abstract}
Quality-Diversity (QD) algorithms aim to discover a diverse set of high-performing solutions instead of a single optimal solution. This project presents an implementation of a QD archive system that stores and evaluates solutions across a behavior space.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
Traditional optimization methods focus on identifying a single optimal solution. However, many real-world problems require multiple diverse solutions. Quality-Diversity (QD) algorithms address this by exploring a variety of high-quality solutions.

\section{Objectives}
The objectives of this project are:
\begin{itemize}
\item To implement a QD archive
\item To evaluate solution quality
\item To preserve diversity in behavior space
\end{itemize}

\section{Methodology}
The workflow includes:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Generate initial solutions
\item Evaluate solutions
\item Map them into a behavior space
\item Store best solutions in archive cells
\item Apply mutation to generate new solutions
\end{enumerate}

\section{Implementation}
The project is implemented in Python and includes:
\begin{itemize}
\item Archive structure
\item Evaluation functions
\item Optimization loop
\end{itemize}

\section{Results}
The system:
\begin{itemize}
\item Produces diverse solutions
\item Maintains high-quality individuals
\item Explores the behavior space effectively
\end{itemize}

\section{Conclusion}
QDArchive demonstrates how Quality-Diversity methods can balance exploration and performance.

\section{Future Work}
Future improvements include visualization, parallelization, and ML integration.

